# CCR Anchor Design Doc

(SMAGE Core — ha_core/transform/anchor.ts)

## 1. Purpose

Anchors are stable, minimal context markers extracted from message history.
They survive compression, dedupe, relevance scoring, and window shaping.
They allow the CCR pipeline to reconstruct essential context without re‑expanding the entire history.
Anchors are the spine of the CCR pipeline.

## 2. Anchor Responsibilities

Anchors must

- A. Preserve essential context
  system instructions
  last user intent
  last assistant output
  last tool result
- B. Survive compression
  Compression may crush messages into summaries or placeholders.
  Anchors must remain intact.
- C. Reconstruct context
  Anchors must be re‑injectable into the shaped window.
- D. Be deterministic
  Same input → same anchors.
- E. Be minimal
  Anchors must not include:
  full history
  irrelevant messages
  noise
  hallucinated content
- F. Be role‑aware
  Anchors must track:
  system
  user
  assistant
  tool
- G. Be order‑preserving
  Anchors must preserve the chronological order of roles.

## Anchor Extraction Rules

### Rule 1 — System messages

Collect all system messages in order.

#### Rule 2 — Last user message

Store the last user message.

#### Rule 3 — Last assistant message

Store the last assistant message.

#### Rule 4 — Last tool message

Store the last tool message.

#### Rule 5 — Deterministic

Extraction must not depend on:
randomness
token counts
classifier output
relevance scoring

#### Rule 6 — No hallucination

Anchors must only contain content from the original messages.

Anchor Reconstruction Rules
Given:
crushed messages
anchor object
Reconstruction must:
Rule 1 — Prepend system anchors
System anchors always come first.
Rule 2 — Insert last user
If present.
Rule 3 — Insert last assistant
If present.
Rule 4 — Insert last tool
If present.
Rule 5 — Preserve order
System → user → assistant → tool.
Rule 6 — Do not modify anchor content
Anchors are immutable.

## Anchor Placement in CCR Pipeline

Anchors sit between:
Before compression
extractAnchor(messages)
After dedupe + relevance + priority + window
applyAnchor(shapedMessages, anchor)
Before output reduction
Anchors ensure the final shaped window contains essential context. 7. Anchor Interaction with Other CCR Stages
Dedupe
Anchors must not be removed by dedupe.
Relevance
Anchors override relevance scoring.
Priority
Anchors always have highest priority.
Window
Anchors must always fit inside the window.
Reconstruction
Anchors are the reconstruction seed.

## Anchor Determinism Requirements

Anchors must produce identical output for identical input.
This ensures:
reproducibility
cache stability
predictable compression
safe MCP behaviour
safe proxy behaviour 9. Anchor Token Budget
Anchors must be small:
system: usually 1–3 messages
lastUser: 1
lastAssistant: 1
lastTool: 1
Total anchor token cost must be < 5% of window. 10. Anchor Test Contract

